Glow
Motivation
  • If we look at a very bright object, light scatters inside our eyes
  • This produces glare (a “glow” around the object)
  • Example photograph: Notice the glare (and lens flares)
    • Gives you a visual hint about brightness
Motivation
  • Glare is often an important visual cue
  • Ex: Consider renderings of this object
  • Which one appears brighter? Why?
Motivation
  • The tube has color (1,1,1) in both cases
  • But the glare image seems brighter
    • And it gives the feel of a very bright purple object
Procedure
  • Glow is pretty easy to implement
    • Render bright parts of scene to an FBO
    • Blur the FBO
    • Render the scene as usual to the screen
    • Using additive blending, add the blurred FBO on top of the normal image
Speedup
  • This is pretty simple, but it has a cost: We must render the entire scene twice
  • Can we do better?
    • Yes!
FBO
  • We need to use a multi-slice FBO
  • Slice 0 will get the ordinary scene colors
  • Slice 1 will get the bright parts of the scene
Declaration
  • Declare like so:
Framebuffer fbo{ 512, 512, 2, GL_RGBA8 };
  • This creates a single-texture, two-slice FBO; each slice has format RGBA8
Glow
  • We need to decide what should produce glow
  • Common choices:
    • Only emitters
    • Emitters + specular highlights
    • Only things that are “pretty bright”
Option 1
  • Suppose we choose “only emitters”
  • Modify the fragment shader:
...inputs as usual...
layout(location=0) out vec4 color;
layout(location=1) out vec4 glow;

void main(){
    vec3 emitColor = texture( emissionTexture, vec3(v_texcoord,0.0)).rgb;
    vec4 baseColor = texture( baseTexture, vec3(v_texcoord,0.0));
    ...shader code as usual...
    glow.rgb = emitColor;
    glow.a = baseColor.a;
}
Option 2
  • Suppose we want emitters + specular highlights
  • Modify the FS:
...inputs as usual...
layout(location=0) out vec4 color;
layout(location=1) out vec4 glow;
void main(){
    ...shader code as usual...
    glow.rgb = totalSpecularAmount + emitColor;
    glow.a = baseColor.a;
}
Option 3
  • What if we want “bright enough” things to produce glow?
  • Add a uniform:
    vec3 colorThreshold;
  • Anything brighter than colorThreshold will produce glow
Option 3
  • In fragment shader:
...inputs as usual...
layout(location=0) out vec4 color;
layout(location=1) out vec4 glow;
void main(){
    ...shader code as usual...
    if( all( lessThan( color.rgb, colorThreshold) ) )
        glow.rgb = vec3(0);
    else
        glow.rgb = smoothstep( vec3(0.0), colorThreshold),  color.rgb );
    glow.a = baseColor.a;
}
Smoothstep
  • What is smoothstep?
  • Syntax: smoothstep( a, b, c )
    • If c < a: Returns zero
    • Else if c > b: Returns 1
    • Else:
      • Let t = (c-a)/(b-a)
      • Return 3t2- 2t3
  • Produces a smooth “ramp”
Procedure
  • We’re ready to go!
  • Here’s the scene we’re doing
Procedure
  • Initialize colorThreshold, if you’re using that approach
Procedure
  • Set fbo as render target and clear it
  • fbo.setAsRenderTarget(true)
Procedure
  • Draw scene
    • Left: What’s in FBO slice 0
    • Right: What’s in FBO slice 1
Procedure
  • Unset fbo as render target
  • fbo.unsetAsRenderTarget(true)
Procedure
  • Blur slice 1 of the fbo
  • fbo.blur(1,radius,1.0f);
    • Larger blur radius spreads the glow more widely
    • If we want more pronounced glow, we can set multiplier to value ≥ 1
Procedure
  • fbo.texture->bind(0);
    • This tells the system to pull data from the fbo’s texture
    • It’s a two-slice texture, so we can get data from either normal render or glow render
Procedure
  • fboshader.use()
  • VS: Typical pass-through
layout(location=0) in vec3 position;
layout(location=1) in vec2 texCoord;
out vec2 v_texCoord;
void main(){
    gl_Position = vec4(position.xy,-1.0,1.0);
    v_texCoord = texCoord;
}
FS
  • Pull normal render (c0), glow render (c1)
layout(binding=0) uniform sampler2DArray tex;
in vec2 v_texCoord;
out vec4 color;
void main(){
    vec4 c0 = texture( tex, vec3(v_texCoord,0 ) );
    vec4 c1 = texture( tex, vec3(v_texCoord,1 ) );
    color.rgb = c0.rgb + c1.rgb;
    color.a = c0.a;
}
Procedure
  • Draw quad over the screen
Note
  • We can make glow more obvious by using a larger kernel or by calling blur() repeatedly or by increasing the multiplier
  • Left: No glow; Middle: 11x11 Gaussian; Right: 11x11 Gaussian, 5 blur()’s
Improvement
  • We can get an improved quality by using several blur textures
  • Ex: Unreal authors (see references) found that using three glow layers (small, medium, large blur radii) worked well
    • For best results, weight the small radius blur twice as much as the medium or large radii blurs
    • We could do this with a 4 slice FBO: Render it, then blur each layer with a different radius
